                                span.ta-c.u-textColor_1-dark #[strong UN reports on Colombian Parapolitics]#[br]#[br]
                                span The United Nations (UN) Special Rapporteur on the Independence of Judges and Lawyers spoke on Wednesday to the UN Human Rights Council about the scandal of politicians’ links to paramilitary groups in Colombia, reports AF P.#[br]
                                span Gabriela Carina Knaul de Albuquerque e Silva, who visited Colombia in December to investigate the condition of #[input.c-input.js-escribir(type="text" placeholder="Text here...")] independence in the country, told the council that “During the last few years, new illegal armed actors have appeared. In this framework, links have been established between paramilitary leaders and politicians, including members of Congress.”#[br]
                                    img(class="u-responsive-img cont-image" src="unit_3/module_12/assets/images/col_5_1.png", alt="")
                                span The UN official explained to the committee that 93 Colombian #[input.c-input.js-escribir(type="text" placeholder="Text here...")] have thus far been charged with illicit ties to paramilitary organizations, and 22 of them have been sentenced by Colombia’s Supreme Court.#[br]
                                span She also noted that authorities have opened investigations into twelve governors, 166 mayors, 58 city councilmen, and thirteen other government officials.#[br]
                                span Despite the relatively large amount of Colombian #[input.c-input.js-escribir(type="text" placeholder="Text here...")] officials implicated in this scandal, known as “parapolitics,” Albuquerque e Silva added that the investigations “have been impeded” by the extradition of paramilitary and criminal leaders to the United States.#[br]
                                span According to Albuquerque e Silva, the extradition of these leaders have prevented the Colombian justice system from hearing testimonies on the paramilitaries’ “relationships with Colombian politicians, primarily congressmen and officials.”#[br]
                                span Earlier in May, it was reported that despite guarantees by the Colombian government, only six of the fourteen former top AUC paramilitary leaders who were extradited to the United States two years ago have been able to offer their testimony in Colombia’s Justice and Peace process, which offered illegal armed groups that demobilized shorter sentences for their cooperation in the justice system.#[br]
                                span Albuquerque e Silva also reiterated previous statements, calling the Justice and Peace process “very slow,” and noted that “not issued a single [judicial] sentence” has been delivered against the thousands of paramilitaries who demobilized under the program.

